{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"268067aa-a68e-4efb-a689-8b40b6ef76bc","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**. Here's why:\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — Downloads and installs the **latest versions** of all installed workloads to match your current SDK. After an SDK update, this is what brings workloads (like `maui`) back in sync.\n\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — Re-installs workloads at their **current versions**. It fixes corrupted or incomplete installations but won't pull newer versions needed by a newer SDK.\n\n**TL;DR:** After a SDK update, the problem is a version mismatch, so `dotnet workload update` is the right fix:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\n```\n\nIf issues persist after that, *then* try `dotnet workload repair` in case something got corrupted during the update.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f982c232-3177-47a8-82c3-0548cf245539","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question — I don't need to explore any codebase.","outputTokens":259,"requestId":"DBD9:33CB43:7B2A6:9BB4E:69F549F4"},"id":"6ba13168-044d-426d-a66e-91c2cc5a6a21","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:48:59.650Z","parentId":"b5c1d651-dda7-4235-9cdf-6c4d6c8058b6"}
